## B. CALCULATION OF REAL AND IMAGINARY PARTS OF THE PROPAGATION MODULE

If $\vec{a}=\vec{\eta}+i \vec{\rho}=\left(\eta_{1}+i \rho_{1}, \eta_{2}+i \rho_{2}, \eta_{3}+i \rho_{3}\right)$, the modules of $\vec{a}\left(\equiv \vec{a}_{+}\right)$and $\vec{a}^{*}\left(\equiv \vec{a}_{-}\right)$are complex numbers that we call $a_{+}$ and $a_{-}$, respectively. To calculate them we state:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& a_{ \pm}=\hat{a} \pm i \bar{a} \quad(\hat{a}, \bar{a} \in \mathbb{R}) \\
& a_{ \pm}^{2}=\vec{\eta}^{2}-\vec{\rho}^{2} \pm i 2 \vec{\eta} \cdot \vec{\rho}=\hat{a}^{2}-\hat{a}^{2} \pm i 2 \hat{a} \bar{a}
\end{aligned}
$$

where we identify the real numbers

$$
\begin{aligned}
& r=\vec{\eta}^{2}-\vec{\rho}^{2}=\hat{a}^{2}-\hat{a}^{2} \\
& q=2 \vec{\eta} \cdot \vec{\rho}=2 \hat{a} \bar{a} \\
& h=\left[r^{2}+q^{2}\right]^{1 / 2}=a_{-} \cdot a_{+}=\hat{a}^{2}+\hat{a}^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Substituting $\hat{a}=q /(2 \hat{a})$ in $r=\hat{a}^{2}-\hat{a}^{2}$ we obtain $4 \hat{a}^{4}+4 r \hat{a}^{2}-q^{2}=$ 0 and find the solutions:

$$
\hat{a}= \pm\left(\frac{ \pm h+r}{2}\right)^{1 / 2}, \quad \bar{a}= \pm\left(\frac{ \pm h-r}{2}\right)^{1 / 2}
$$

The signs acompanying $h$ must be chosen positive for $\hat{a}, \bar{a} \in \mathbb{R}$. Regarding the outer signs of the roots, one is tempted to choose the sign of $\hat{a}$ positive because $\hat{a}$ works as an attenuation factor. LD85 solved a similar problem to this before us, imposing positive sign for a proportional quantity equivalent to our $\hat{a}$ (which they called $\alpha$ ). However this imposition is unnecesary to solve the above equations and is not suitable for a general case in which stimulated emission could dominate. Note that the total absorption coefficient $\eta_{0} \pm|\hat{a}|>0$, appearing e.g. in the eigenvalues of the propagation matrix or in the expressions of the evolution operator, is always positive with $\eta_{0}>0$ and $|\hat{a}|<\eta_{0}$ when stimulated emission does not dominate. For this reason, we avoid to impose the outer signs, labelling them as $\bar{s}$ and $\bar{s}$ :

$$
\hat{a}=\bar{s}\left(\frac{h+r}{2}\right)^{1 / 2}, \quad \bar{a}=\bar{s}\left(\frac{h-r}{2}\right)^{1 / 2}
$$

The signs are however constrained by the angle $\theta$ between $\vec{\eta}$ and $\vec{\rho}$ in the QUV space, because $\bar{s} \cdot \bar{s}=\operatorname{sign}(\hat{a} \cdot \bar{a})=$ $\operatorname{sign}(\vec{\eta} \cdot \vec{\rho})=\operatorname{sign}(\cos \theta)$. Thus, when $\vec{\eta} \perp \vec{\rho}$ the signs are undetermined, but then the expressions involucrating them become independent on them.
